1265":"1265","about 1375":"circa 1375","1339":"1339","Bramall Hall, Bramhall, Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Bramhall, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stockport, Greater Manchester, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, England","Bromhall, Cheshire, England":"Broomhall, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1310–about 1375":"1310–about 1375","1302–Female":"1302–Deceased","1304–Female":"1304–Deceased","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1321–1368":"1321–1368","1322–1339":"1322–1339","1340–1403":"1340–1403","–Female":"Deceased","1265–1315":"1265–1315","1260–Female":"1260–Deceased","1340":"1340","1260":"1260","1315":"1315","1403":"1403","1304":"1304","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1334":"1334","1322":"1322","1310":"1310","1321":"1321","1375":"1375","1265":"1265","about 1375":"about 1375","1339":"1339","Bramall Hall, Bramhall, Wrenbury, Cheshire, England":"Bramhall, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Stockport, Greater Manchester, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Stockport, Cheshire, England","Bromhall, Cheshire, England":"Broomhall, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bromhall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Broomhall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Broomhall","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Broomhall (Cheshire), Broomhall Grange in Tyrley and Broom Hall Farm in Brewood (both Staffordshire), Broomhall Farms in Kempsey (Worcestorshire), or Broomhall in Sunningdale (Berkshire, formerly in Windlesham in Surrey), all of which take their name from Old English <i>brōm</i> ‘broom, gorse’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, hollow’.","variant of the similar Cheshire name   Bramhall  , which also has early forms in <i>-o-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey de Bromhall was born in 1310, in Broomhall, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard de Bromhall I, was 45 and his mother, Mrs. Margery Bromhall, was 51. He married Margery Wettenhall in 1334, in Stockport, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died about 1375, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1310–about 1375":"1310–umbes 1375","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1321–1368":"1321–1368","1322–1339":"1322–1339","1340–1403":"1340–1403","–Female":"Surn